          %h2 Welcome to the BBC Capstone Project Homepage!
        %h5 Objective:
        %p.justify-col
          Our project objective was to create a cheaper hardware version of an automatic generator backup controller for an external battery than what already exists on the open market.
          The hardware controller should automatically start and stop a generator based on the current external battery’s voltage levels.
          The generator should automatically charge the battery when the voltage drops below a certain threshold value.
          The generator should automatically turn off when the external battery is sufficiently charged.
        %h5 Project Description:
        %p.justify-col
          The Automatic Generator Battery Backup Controller (or simply
          =succeed "," do
            %i BBC
          as we call it) is a hardware system regulated by an
          =link_to "Adruino Uno Microcontroller", "https://www.ebay.com/itm/ATmega328P-CH340G-UNO-R3-Board-USB-Cable-Compatible-with-Arduino-L2/173019953288"
          and controlled by a Arduino compatible
          =link_to "Liquid Crystal Display", "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liquid-crystal_display"
          (
          %i LCD
          ). The
          %i BBC
          system can help those who depend on solar power, especially those in developing nations. It eliminates the need to manually start and stop a generator, making the generator more convenient and efficient.
          %br
          %br
          The
          %i BBC
          system connects to general purpose generators and monitors an external battery's voltage. When the external battery's voltage drops below a user specified threshold (
          %i 11.0V ~ 12.0V
          =succeed "," do
            )
          the
          %i BBC
          system activates the generator's starter, for a user specified amount of time (
          %i 2.0s ~ 3.0s in increments of 0.1s
          =succeed "," do
            )
          in an attempt to power on the generator. If the generator successfully starts and the external battery's voltage reaches a separate user specified threshold (
          %i 13.0V ~ 14.0V
          =succeed "," do
            )
          the
          %i BBC
          system powers off the generator and waits for the external battery's voltage to deplete again, then repeats. If the generator fails to power on, the
          %i BBC
          system delays for a user specified amount of time (
          %i 20 ~ 60s
          =succeed "," do
            )
          before activating the generator's starter again. The
          %i BBC
          system is only allowed three iterations of failed starter attempts in succession before displaying an error and taking appropriate action.
          %br
          %br
          An
          =link_to "Arduino Keypad Shield Display", "https://www.banggood.com/Keypad-Shield-Blue-Backlight-For-Arduino-Robot-LCD-1602-Board-p-79326.html"
          shows a main menu with live information about the external battery's voltage and allows the user to control the minimum and maximum generator threshold voltages, the between-iteration delay time, and the generator's starter duration. If the attached generator does not power on within the alotted amount of starter time and iterations, the
          %i BBC
          system displays an error message (
          %i Starter Failure!
          ), lights up the red
          =link_to "Light Emitting Diode", "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Light-emitting_diode"
          (
          %i LED
          )
          indicator, and halts itself to be reset. The
          %i BBC
          system reset feature is to help prevent burn-out of the starter or generator during operation.
          %br
          %br
          At any time while viewing the main menu, a user can toggle the system's automation status or adjust the system parameters.
          Using the
          %i UP
          and
          %i DOWN
          buttons on the
          %i LCD
          allows the user set/toggle the automation status, determining if the system should automatically try to start and stop the generator, or not.
          This feature is useful during system maintenance and any executive reasons for system stagnation.
          Using the
          %i LEFT
          and
          %i RIGHT
          buttons allows the user to specify all the aforementioned "user specified values".
          These values are moderately variable to give the user a more dynamic and optimized controller for their particular generator.
          At any time within the parameter selection menu, the user can press
          %i SELECT
          to immediately leave the parameter selection menu and set all the parameter values to their current or changed states without needing to scroll through each parameter unecessarily.
          The parameter selection feature also uses on-board
          =link_to "Electronically Erasable Programmable Read-Only Memory", "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/EEPROM"
          (
          %i EEPROM
          ) to read and set the parameter values.
          This feature persists parameter values through menu changes, system resets, and power outages to easily keep optimized settings.
          %br
          %br
          The
          %i BBC
          system also has a feature that turns off the
          %i LCD
          display after 10 or more seconds of user inactivity (not pressing any of the buttons on the
          %i LCD
          keypad). When the
          %i LCD
          is off and the user presses
          %i SELECT
          , the
          %i LCD
          turns on and the system returns to its current state.
          If the user has set the automation status to "ON", the system will run as normal in the background, even if the
          %i LCD
          is off.
          This inactivity feature is useful to save power/energy over the lifespan of the
          %i BBC
          system, to help prevent burn-out of the
          =succeed "," do
            %i LCD
          and to help prevent unintentional system manipulation from outside sources.
